data.name: PlasticBedHeatupOnFLs
data.value: The build plate temperature on first layers is the table temperature which is kept constant only on first layers below height defined in settings. It should be high enough for a part immediately and securely glues to a table.

data.name: PlasticBedTemperature
data.value: The build plate temperature is the table constant temperature throughout all printing process except printing first layers. Set this value high enough so a part won't detache and edges won't bend.

data.name: PlasticCoastAtEndLength
data.value: The coast length is the length of the last polygon segment which is printed without plastic extrusion. Plastic goes out only by gravity on this coast segment. Choose length enough to stop free plastic spilling after retract, however, keep an eye on underextrusion.

data.name: PlasticCoolingEnable
data.value: Enable print cooling is the flag of fan on/off for cooling extruders. For best results, turn on cooling with any print.

data.name: PlasticCoolingFirstLayersFanHeight
data.value: The first layers fan speed height is the height below which cooling rules are special. Choose a minimum but sufficient height so a part is securely glued to a bed and part geometry won't lose its geometry by bed heating.

data.name: PlasticCoolingFirstLayersFanSpeed
data.value: Choose the fan speed low enough for better adhesion to a bed and to prevent geometry changes due to bed heating.

data.name: PlasticCoolingMaximumFanSpeed
data.value: The maximum fan speed is the fan speed for cooling, which is used when layer time is less than minimal layer time (specified in settings). Indicated as percentage. Choose maximum speed to have no form meltings and geometry distorsions.

data.name: PlasticCoolingMinLayerTimeForCooling
data.value: The layer time for max fan speed is the time when edges of a part start melting and the part losing its geometry integrity with regular fan speed.

data.name: PlasticCoolingRegularFanSpeed
data.value: The regular fan speed is the fan speed for cooling while all printing process except printing first layers. Indicated as percentage. Choose high enough for saving part geometry undisturbed, but not too high for layers start losing good adhesion beetwen themselves.

data.name: Error
data.value: error.png;System.Drawing.Bitmap, System.Drawing, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b03f5f7f11d50a3a

data.name: PlasticExtraLength
data.value: The extra unretract length is the value additional to retract length. On print resuming, if portion of plastic has spilled from an extruder, then volume of plastic in a nozzle becomes less than what it was before travel. If you have noticed for this plastic (especcially for runny) that at the beginning of print there is an underextrusion migrating to normal extrusion, then you shoud set not null for this parameter.

data.name: PlasticExtraSpeed
data.value: The unretract speed is the speed of direct movement of plastic in a feeder. Choose maximum for fast printing restart, however, keep in mind that some feeders can't handle fast feeding speed.

data.name: PlasticExtrusionMultiplier
data.value: The flow multiplier is a correction factor of plastic extrusion. Vary this parameter if all parts have under- or overextrusion.

data.name: PlasticFilamentDiameter
data.value: The filament diameter of plastic thread is measured in cross section. Usually it is 1.75mm or 3mm. You can find this value on the package of plastic filament.

data.name: FilamentDiameterLabel
data.value: GlobalFilamentDiameter

data.name: ImgPlasticFilamentDiameter
data.value: filament diameter.jpg;System.Drawing.Bitmap, System.Drawing, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b03f5f7f11d50a3a

data.name: PlasticFirstLayersHeightMM
data.value: The first layers temperatures height is the height below which extruders and a table have special heating rules.

data.name: ImgPlasticFirstLayersFanSpeedHeight
data.value: ..\..\Resources\First layers fan speed height.png;System.Drawing.Bitmap, System.Drawing, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b03f5f7f11d50a3a

data.name: PlasticRetractionLengthOnChangingExtruder
data.value: The retraction length on tool change is the length of plastic reverse movement in a feeder. Choose maximum length, taking into account the fact that plastic won't be fed into this tool for a long time and it is necessary to prevent plastic leakings due to gravity.

data.name: PlasticRetractionLengthOnTravel
data.value: The retraction length is the length of plastic reverse movement in a feeder. Choose long enough length to stop pressure onto plastic in an extruder chamber. Keep in mind that during retract, the extruder stays still, so the longer retract, the longer it stays without movement, which can lead to part melting by the extruder, and leakings for runny plastics.

data.name: PlasticRetractionSpeed
data.value: The retract speed is the speed of reverse movement of plastic in a feeder. Choose maximum for fast printing restart, however, keep in mind that some feeders can't handle fast feeding speed.

data.name: PlasticRetractMinimumTravelNoCrossing
data.value: The retraction minimum travel is the sufficient travel length before retraction. In case of short travels it makes no sence to stop for retraction because plastic has not enough time to spill out uncontrolled. Choose this value to maximum, but beware of plastic leaks while travels.

data.name: PlasticTemperatureOnFLs
data.value: The extruder temperature on first layers is the extruder printing temperature which is kept constant only on first layers - below height defined in settings.

data.name: PlasticTemperaturePrint
data.value: The extruder temperature is the temperature at which plastic will be melted for extruding from a nozzle. You can find an appropriate temperature range on the plastic filament package.

data.name: PlasticTemperatureWait
data.value: The standby extruder temperature is the extruder temperature at which it will be in an inactive state (another extruder is active, i.e. is printing). It should be as close as possible to printing temperature for faster heatup and print start, but low enough to prevent plastic free flow out from an extruder by gravity.

data.name: PlasticWipeNozzleLength
data.value: The wipe nozzle length is the length of reverse print head movement. The print head is moving in reverse after retract and is wiping spilling plastic on already printed lines. Choose length enough for stop free plastic spilling after retract.

data.name: PlasticZHopP
data.value: The Z-hop height is the extruder lift up height when moving between print areas. Choose minimum for fast printing process, but enough for prevent part edges hitting and as a result bringing and leaving beads on a part shell. Z-hop may lead formation of strings, however, it is usually easier remove this than removing beads.

data.name: FiberEndPolygonEmptyDistanceMM
data.value: Finish ironing distance is the length of travel which is performed by a composite nozzle at the end of fiber polygon in the direction of last segment. It happens after cut and full exit a of fiber tail. This movement is needed for ironing tail which, if not done, will be fluffy.

data.name: FiberDiameter
data.value: The fiber diameter is the average diameter of a fiber thread measured in cross section. For the Anisoprint CCF-1.5k this value is 0.34mm.

data.name: FiberExtraSpeed
data.value: Fiber extrusion speed is the speed of the fiber tail extrusion.

data.name: FiberExtrusionMultiplier
data.value: The plastic flow multiplier is a factor by which amount of extruded plastic in a composite extruder is multiplied. Vary this parameter if all composite polygons have under- or overextrusion.

data.name: LinearDensity
data.value: Linear density is the mass of 1km of fiber in grams.

data.name: FiberZHopF
data.value: Z-lift on restart is the height at which a composite extruder is raised to put out a fiber tail and start to print a composite polygon.

data.name: FiberZHopFPauseAdhesion
data.value: Restart pause is the delay before start of composite polygon printing. This is needed for the good adhesion between a fiber tail and an a underlying layer.

data.name: PrinterAdditionalRetract
data.value: The additional retract length is the additional length of plastic reverse movement in a feeder which will be added to the retract length value for used plastics. Use this parameter if your printer has bowden tube for plastic feeding, because in this case retraction inertia may appear.

data.name: PrinterEndGCode
data.value: The end G-code is the code which is executed at the end of print process.

data.name: PrinterHasHeatedTable
data.value: The has heated table flag is the flag which indicates if a printer has heatable table.

data.name: PrinterHeight
data.value: The height is the size of build area along the Z axis.

data.name: PrinterInset0Acceleration
data.value: The external shell acceleration is the acceleration which is used only for external shell printing. It has affect on travels and moves with extrusion.

data.name: PrinterInset0Jerk
data.value: The external shell jerk is the jerk value which is used only for external shell printing. It has affect on travels and moves without extrusion.

data.name: PrinterLength
data.value: The depth is the size of build area along the Y axis.

data.name: PrinterOnChangeExtruderUpMM
data.value: The Z-lift on tool change is the height at which a print head raises for tool change.

data.name: PrinterOthersAcceleration
data.value: The regular acceleration is the acceleration which is used for all printing areas except an external shell. It has affect on travels and moves with extrusions.

data.name: PrinterOthersJerk
data.value: The regular jerk is the jerk which is used for all printing areas except an external shell. It has affect on travels and moves with extrusion.

data.name: PrinterStartGCode
data.value: The start G-code is the code which is executed at the start of print process.

data.name: PrinterTravelSpeedXY
data.value: The X/Y travel speed is the linear speed of print head movements in XY plane without extrusions.

data.name: PrinterTravelSpeedZ
data.value: The Z travel speed is the linear speed of print head movements in the Z direction without extrusion.

data.name: PrinterUseAccelerations
data.value: The enable acceleration control is the flag of manual control over acceleartions.

data.name: PrinterUseJerks
data.value: The enable jerk control is the flag of manual control over jerks.

data.name: PrinterWidth
data.value: The width is the size of build area along the X axis.

data.name: ExtruderFanIndex
data.value: The cooling fan index is the number of this cooling fan in printer firmware.

data.name: ExtruderHasFan
data.value: The has cooling fan flag is the flag which indicates thar extruder has a nozzle cooling fan.

data.name: ExtruderNozzleDiameter
data.value: The nozzle diameter is the diameter of the outlet hole of a nozzle.

data.name: ExtruderOffsetX
data.value: X offset is the extruder X offset relative to the base point on a print head. If your printer has only one extruder then set this parameter to zero. If printer firmware doesn't set offset by itself then you should set other extruders offsets relative to base (usually first) extruder. In this case you sholud set offsets for this base extruder offsets to zero.

data.name: ExtruderOffsetY
data.value: Y offset is the extruder Y offset relatively to the base point on a print head. If your printer has only one extruder then set this parameter to zero. If printer firmware doesn't set offset by itself then you should set other extruders offsets relative to base (usually first) extruder. In this case you sholud set offsets for this base extruder offsets to zero.

data.name: ExtruderOffsetZ
data.value: Z offset is the extruder Z offset relatively to the base point on a print head. If your printer has only one extruder then set this parameter to zero. If printer firmware doesn't set offset by itself then you should set other extruders offsets relative to base (usually first) extruder. In this case you sholud set offsets for this base extruder offsets to zero.

data.name: ExtruderPFCutCode
data.value: The cut G-code is the code, that actuates fiber cutting. This value should be set only by printer manufacturer.

data.name: ExtruderPFCutDistance
data.value: The cut distance is the distance from a cut point to outlet hole of a nozzle. This value should be set only by printer manufacturer.

data.name: ExtruderPFExtraLength
data.value: The fiber restart length is the length of fiber extrusion during restart. This is necessary for the fiber tail to get out of the nozzle. This parameter in general should equal to the cut distance.

data.name: ProfilePartAllowGenerateFiber
data.value: The use fiber flag is the flag which indicates that parts may be reinforced with fiber.

data.name: ProfilePartGenerateBrim
data.value: The generate brim flag is the flag which indicates that the Aura will generate brims for parts. The brim is the extended contour of a part on a first layer. Use brim to prevent part stick-off from table surface during printing process.

data.name: ProfilePartGenerateFiberPerimeters
data.value: The generate reinforced perimeters flag is the flag which indicates that the Aura will generate reinforced perimeters for printed parts.

data.name: ProfilePartGenerateSkirt
data.value: The generate skirt is the flag which indicates that the Aura will generate skirts for parts. The skirt is the extended contour of a part on a first layer. Use skirt to stabilize plastic flow in extruder before main printing.

data.name: ProfilePartGenerateSupport
data.value: The generate support flag is the flag which indicates that the Aura will generate supports for parts. The support is used to prevent the fall of overhanging parts.

data.name: ProfilePartGenerateWipeTower
data.value: The generate wipe tower flag is the flag which indicates that the Aura will generate wipe tower for parts. The wipe tower is a service part that is being printed at the same time as main parts. The wipe tower is used to clean nozzles on tool change.

data.name: ProfilePartInfillCPercent
data.value: The fill density percent is the percent of filled space inside the shell.

data.name: ProfilePartInfillSBottomTopLayerCount
data.value: The top/bottom solid layers count is the number of layers in which solid infill will be generated. The solid infill will be generated in special spots - where a layer contacts with external environment.

data.name: ProfilePartInsetFInnerCount
data.value: The inner reinforced perimeters count is the number of perimeters which will reinforce inner holes (not surface) of a part.

data.name: ProfilePartInsetFOuterCount
data.value: The outer reinforced perimeters count is the number of perimeters which will reinforce outer surface(not holes) of a part.

data.name: ProfilePartInsetX0Count
data.value: The external shell perimeters is the number of perimeters which build the plastic external shell - the most precise one.

data.name: ProfilePartInsetXPInnerWhenFiberCount
data.value: The plastic perimeters count inside fiber is the number of perimeters between fiber and cellular infill.

data.name: ProfilePartInsetXPOnlyCount
data.value: The plastic perimeters count is the number of perimeters which build the plastic internal shell. It provides solidity of part surface.

data.name: ProfilePartInsetXPOuterWhenFiberCount
data.value: The plastic perimeters count outside fiber is the number of perimeters between external shell and fiber perimeters.

data.name: ImgPlasticInfillSolidAngleStep
data.value: ..\..\Resources\ImgPlasticInfillSolidAngleStep.png;System.Drawing.Bitmap, System.Drawing, Version=4.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=b03f5f7f11d50a3a

data.name: ProfileBrimEWCoeff
data.value: The extrusion width coefficient is the nozzle diameter multiplication factor. That is extrusion width = nozzle diameter * coefficient.

data.name: ProfileBrimLoops
data.value: The brim loops count is the number of brim loops around a part. The more loops, the adhesion between parts and a table is stronger.

data.name: ProfileFLEWCoeffToNormal
data.value: The first layer extrusion width coefficient is the extrusion width multiplication factor. It has affect on extrusion width for all entities on first layer and consequently on plastic amount.

data.name: ProfileFLSpeed
data.value: The first layer printing speed is the speed of printing of all entities at the first layer. You may want to set this value a little slower than average speed on other layers to improve adhesion between parts and a table.

data.name: ProfileFLThickness
data.value: The first layer height is the height of the first layer. Set this parameter a little bit larger that other microlayers to compensate table relief. The first layer has no microlayers structure as macrolayer and it doesn't comprise into any macrolayer as other microlayers.

data.name: ProfileInfillPCEWCoeff
data.value: The extrusion width coefficient is the nozzle diameter multiplication factor. That is extrusion width = nozzle diameter * coefficient.

data.name: ProfileInfillPCSpeed
data.value: The printing speed is the speed which will be applied to plastic infill printing. Set this parameter as high as possible to speed up printing process.

data.name: ProfileInfillPCStartingAngle
data.value: The fill starting angle is the angle of infill rotation.

data.name: ProfileInfillPCType
data.value: Fill pattern. You could choose from three patterns: lines, grid or triangles, depending on your preferences.

data.name: ProfileInfillPSAngleStep
data.value: The fill angle offset is the offset angle which is added to current infill rotation angle on each layer. For example, if fill angle offset is 10°, on first macro layer angle is 0°, on second is 10°, on third is 20° etc.

data.name: ProfileInfillPSEWCoeff
data.value: The extrusion width coefficient is the nozzle diameter multiplication factor. That is extrusion width = nozzle diameter * coefficient

data.name: ProfileInfillPSMacroLayersOntoFiberCount
data.value: The solid plastic layers above fiber count is the number of macrolayers in which solid infill will be generated. This parameter not used as solid plastic layers below fiber, so you may want to use it only for cover up fiber polygons from above.

data.name: ProfileInfillPSMacroLayersUnderFiberCount
data.value: The solid plastic layers below fiber count is the number of macrolayers in which solid infill will be generated. It needs to prevent fiber fall through cellular infill.

data.name: ProfileInfillPSSpeed
data.value: The printing speed is the speed which will be applied to plastic infill printing. Set this parameter as high as possible to speed up printing process.

data.name: ProfileInfillPSStartingAngle
data.value: The fill starting angle is the starting angle of infill rotation.

data.name: ProfileInset0EWCoeff
data.value: The extrusion width coefficient is the nozzle diameter multiplication factor. That is extrusion width = nozzle diameter * coefficient.

data.name: ProfileInset0Speed
data.value: The printing speed is the speed which will be applied to external shell printing. Set this parameter to the sufficient minimum to improve surface quality of parts. The slower printing speed, the lower chance to obtain vertical ringing on parts.

data.name: ProfileInsetXFEW
data.value: The extrusion width is the width of composite material (plastic + fiber).

data.name: ProfileInsetXFExtrusionFiberMaxPercent
data.value: The fiber feedrate is the percent of full presumed path length. Descrease this parameter to increase fiber tension and increase this parameter to descrease fiber tension.

data.name: ProfileInsetXFSpeed
data.value: The printing speed coefficient is the multiplication factor which will be applied to fiber print speeds.

data.name: ProfileInsetXPEWCoeff
data.value: The extrusion width coefficient is the nozzle diameter multiplication factor. That is extrusion width = nozzle diameter * coefficient.

data.name: ProfileInsetXPSpeed
data.value: The printing speed is the speed which will be applied to plastic perimeters printing. Set this parameter as high as possible to speed up printing process.

data.name: ProfileLayerThicknessInfillRatioToMacro
data.value: The infill layer height is the height of layers which contain cellular infill. The cellular infill is inside plastic perimeters and leaves an empty space in a part.

data.name: ProfileLayerThicknessInset0RatioToMacro
data.value: The external shell height is the height of thin plastic layers which build up an external shell of a part. The thinner external shell, the more precise and accurate the part looks.

data.name: ProfileLayerThicknessInsetXPRatioToMacro
data.value: The plastic perimeters layer height is the height of thick plastic shell. Set this value as much as possible to speed up the print process. Because plastic perimeters are not visible they can be printed thicker than an external shell to speed up the printing process.

data.name: ProfileLayerThicknessMacroLayerHeight
data.value: The macrolayer height is the height of a layer package which contains microlayers. The microlayer is the layer which contains one or more print entities with the same height. The macrolayer contains microlayers and its structure is defined by microlayer heights. For example, macrolayer height = 0.6mm, external shell height = 0.2mm, plastic perimeters height = 0.3mm, fiber layer height is always equal to macrolayer height and now it is 0.6mm. Accordinally, in this macrolayer we have 4 microlayers. First on 0.2mm and it has only external shell for printing. Second on 0.3mm and it has only plastic perimeters. Third on 0.4mm and it has only external shell. And the last one on 0.6mm and it has external shell, plastic perimeters and fiber perimeters.

data.name: ProfileLayerThicknessSSThickRatioToMacro
data.value: The thick support layer height is the height of layers which contain thick supports. The thick support is calcalated by intersection of thin support layers. Set thick support layer height as large as possible to speed up the print process.

data.name: ProfileLayerThicknessSSThinRatioToMacro
data.value: The thin support layer height is the height of layers which contain thin supports. Thin supports are generated in the areas which can't be converted into thick support.

data.name: ProfileOozePreventionDoAvoidCrossingPerimeters
data.value: The avoid crossing borders flag is the flag which indicates that border crossing minimization mode in on. It means that if it is possible to travel from one print area to another without crossing borders, that path will be chosen instead of direct path with borders crossing . This mode increases print time, but improves external surface quality.

data.name: ProfileOozePreventionDoCoastAtEnd
data.value: The do coast before retract is the flag which indicates that plastic polygon will have dry (without plastic feeding) segments in the end.

data.name: ProfileOozePreventionDoRetractOnLayerChange
data.value: The do retract on changing layers is the flag which indicates that plastic will be retracted on layer change even if there is no XY movements during change layers.

data.name: ProfileOozePreventionDoRetractOnlyWhenCrossingPerimeters
data.value: The do retract only when crossing borders is the flag which indicates that only crossing perimeter travels will have retracts before them. Choose that mode to speed up print process. Plastic that running from nozzle on travels will be all inside a part, so it will not be visible. If you want to do retract before all travels you should uncheck this flag.

data.name: ProfileOozePreventionDoWipeNozzle
data.value: The do wipe nozzle flag is the flag which indicates that plastic polygon will have reverse movement after full polygon print has ended.

data.name: ProfileOozePreventionDoZHop
data.value: The do z-hop when retracted flag is the flag which switches on/off a nozzle z-hop mode when travel has retract. Choose this mode to improve external shell surface quality, but keep in mind that it sligtly slow down print process. Besides, it may produce strings between print areas, but usually it is easier to remove them than plastic drops.

data.name: ProfileOtherCoolingMinLayerTimeForSlowing
data.value: The minimum layer print time. If layer print time is less that this parameter value, the printing speed will be reduced.

data.name: ProfileOtherInfillPSExtendIntoPerimeter
data.value: The infill extension into perimeters is the length by which infill penetrate perimeters. Choose the length that provides infills fusion together with perimeters.

data.name: ProfileOtherTrimGapRatio
data.value: When this parameter is 0 plastic polygon is fully closed. When this parameter is 1, plastic polygon has empty gap that is equal to extrusion width. Choose the value that is differ from 0, if you've seen the plastic overextrusions on polygon seam.

data.name: ProfileSkirtDistance
data.value: The distance from part is the distance between skirt and part.

data.name: ProfileSkirtLoops
data.value: The skirt loops count is the number of skirt loops around a part. Choose the sufficient number to stabilize plastic flow by the end of printing the skirt.

data.name: ProfileSSAirGapToBottom
data.value: The bottom airgap thin layers count is the number of layers between the bottom of a support and the top of a part. Choose a value with which support will be easy to tear from a part and support will not fall down because of large distance to a part.

data.name: ProfileSSAirGapToUp
data.value: The top airgap thin layers count is the number of layers between the top of a support and the bottom of a part. Choose a value with which support will be easy to tear from a part and supported areas will not fall down because of large distance to a support.

data.name: ProfileSSDoAirGap
data.value: The make airgaps flag is the flag which indicates that air gaps will be generated onto and/or under supports.

data.name: ProfileSSEWCoeffThickAndThin
data.value: The extrusion width coefficient is the nozzle diameter multiplication factor. That is extrusion width = nozzle diameter * coefficient.

data.name: ProfileSSGenerateInternalSupport
data.value: The generate support in holes is the flag which indicates that support will be generated not only on the outside of part but in holes too.

data.name: ProfileSSGeneratePerimeters
data.value: The generate shell for support is the flag which indicates that external shell will be generated for supports.

data.name: ProfileSSInfillPercent
data.value: The fill density percent is the percent of filled space inside the support.

data.name: ProfileSSInfillType
data.value: Fill pattern. You could choose from three patterns: lines, grid or triangles, depending on your preferences.

data.name: ProfileSSSelfSupportAngle
data.value: The max unsopported overhang angle up to which part overhang has no need to be supported. If angle is more than the unsupported angle then supports will be generated. The angle is regarding to vertical axe.

data.name: ProfileSSSpeedThick
data.value: The thick support printing speed is the speed which will be applied to thick support printing. Set this parameter as high as possible to speed up printing process.

data.name: ProfileSSSpeedThin
data.value: The thin support printing speed is the speed which will be applied to thin support printing. Set this parameter as high as possible to speed up printing process.

data.name: ProfileSSStartingAngle
data.value: The fill angle is the angle of infill rotation.

data.name: ProfileSSXYDistanceFromObject
data.value: The horizontal X/Y distance from model is the offset from a part to supports. Set this parameter to a part has no fusion with supports.

data.name: FiberDoPlasticRetract
data.value: The do plastic retract flag is the flag which indicates that plastic retract should be performed during composite printing.

data.name: ProfilePartInfillFiberType
data.value: The fiber infill pattern. You may choose from four patterns: solid, rombic grid, isogrid and anisogrid.

data.name: ProfilePartAnisogridRibPlacementType
data.value: The anisogrid ribs crossing type. You may choose from two types: first is when all crossing will be laying near one mutual vertex and second is when transverse rib will be laying on the middles of main (side) ribs.

data.name: ProfileInfillFiberSolidAngleList
data.value: The guide directions is the angles of reinfircing infill lines in a layer. You shoud divide angles with / character. For example, the "60/-60/0" string will result on the 1st layer 60° angle of infill lines, on the 2nd layer -60° angle of infill lines, on the 3rd layer 0°, on the 4th layer 60°, on the 5th layer -60°, on the 6th layer 0° e.t.c

data.name: ProfileInfillFiberSolidEW
data.value: The extrusion width is the width of composite material (plastic + fiber).

data.name: ProfileInfillFiberSolidExtendIntoPerimeters
data.value: The infill extension into perimeters is the distance by which infill penetrates perimeters. Choose the length that provides infills fusion together with perimeters.

data.name: ProfileInfillFiberSolidExtrusionFiberMaxPercent
data.value: The fiber feedrate is the percentage of full presumed path length. Decrease this parameter to raise fiber tension and increase this parameter to decrease fiber tension.

data.name: ProfileInfillFiberSolidMinSegmentLength
data.value: The minimum line length is the length of shortest line that can be printed as it is (with/without prolonging and with/without connection in polygon with other infill lines).

data.name: ProfileInfillFiberSolidSpeedCoefficient
data.value: The printing speed coefficient is the multiplication factor which will be applied to fiber print speeds.
